      "problemTitle": "Why does skin still feel tight if HA works?",
      "problemBody": "<p>Hyaluronic acid, often shortened to HA, is a <strong>humectant</strong>: it attracts and binds water in the outer layers of skin. In practice, that can mean faster plumping and less dryness, especially when applied to damp skin. <em>Sodium hyaluronate</em> is a common salt form used in serums.</p><p>But here’s the limit. HA does not build lipids, ceramides, or the other structures that make up a resilient barrier. If your skin is losing too much water through <strong>transepidermal</strong> water loss, a pure hydration trick may help briefly without fixing the actual problem. Molecular weight matters too: larger molecules stay more on the surface, smaller ones may go a bit deeper, but the effect is still mainly hydration, not repair.</p><p>Studies on HA usually look positive, but many are short, small, or combine several ingredients. That makes <strong>study bias</strong> worth keeping in mind. In plain language: HA is useful, but it’s not the magic barrier fix marketing likes to suggest.</p>",
